As temperatures plummet like
they did last week, students
should be aware of injuries
from cold. Frostbite is a local-
ized cold injury caused by
exposure to freezing tempera-
tures. Body parts that are
exposed are most often affected
(ears, nose, cheeks, ﬁngers and
toes). '

Frostbite is classified as super-
ficial or deep. Superficial injury
involves the skin and subcuta-
neous tissue. The first warning
sign may be intense pain in fin-
gers or feet. The injured area
becomes white, waxy, soft and
numb. Upon thawing, the area
becomes flushed and painful.
Large blisters may develop
within 24 hours and last for
about 10 days. Throbbing pain
may last for several weeks and
the affected area may be sensi-
tive to heat and cold for

months.

Deep frostbite causes injury
to the skin, subcutaneous tis-
sue, muscle, tendon and neu-
rovascular structures. The
injured part is hard and solid
and remains  
cold, mottled 
and blue or gray  A
after thawing.
Edema occurs in
the entire area
and may take
months to re-
solve.

