THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 3, 1994

Out with old, in with the new

There have been some changes in the student hous-

ing applications process. Next year’s incoming class.

and this year’s first-year class are both guaranteed on-

-campus housing for next year. What this means is that

there are only 515 beds left for the upper class.

These are to be distributed by means of a new coin-
puterized lottery. The housing department says this sys-
tem is statistically more fair than the one used in previ-
ous years.

The upper class students have been misled. They are
no longer getting the fair access to housing that they
had before the changes.

There is no longer any seniority for these students. In
previous years, sophomores, juniors and seniors drew
lottery tickets for housing. Of the students who had
valid lottery numbers, seniors were given first choice,
then juniors, then sophomores.

Bob Hopkins, the Director of Housing Services said
that Housing is trying to focus on younger students to
help in the transition to college life. He also said this
policy comes in part from student reaction to polls con-
ducted last year by the Resident Student Association.

Incoming students should be guaranteed housing for
their first year. They don’t have the opportunity of the
previous year to find housing. They also have a large
adjustment from high school to ‘college and need the
chance to meet people in a structured setting.

The university draws students in and then tells them
they will be housed for only the first two years.
However, after more than two years, it isn’t feasible to
transfer from one school to another. Therefore, stu-
dents are stuck in the system and are faced with few
options. The university is not showing concern for
those students it knows won’t leave. '

Competition for. apartments will be earlier and more
intense. Students will begin looking for apartments
sooner and students will have to make the decision of
whether to wait to see if their lottery ticket is valid or
find an apartment and sign a lease they can’t get out
of. Out—of-town students are particularly stuck.

The university has purchased a building on Centre
Avenue. Originally it was intended primarily for gradu-
ate students, but now is to be offered to undergradu-
ates to help absorb the overﬂow from the on-campus
housing. It seems that all students, from this year’s
sophomore class up to graduate students, are being
shafted by these changes.

Students who have spent their time on this campus
