By Ryan Buneher
Asst. Sports Editor

The Pitt women’s basketball team had
never beaten the Miami Hurricanes
before this season. Last night, as the
Lady Panthers went for the season
sweep in Miami, they had to do some-
thing they had not done all season.

“We haverrt had to come back from a
double-figure deficit and win a game,
and we did it,” Pitt head coach Kirk
Bruce said.

The Lady Panthers rebounded, shot,
defended (you get the point) from a 12-
point second-half disadvantage to win
59-53, raising their record to 15-3, 9-1 in
the Big East. Miami is now 7-12, 4-7 in
the conference.

Pitt dug itself a hole by not scoring a
pointfor nearly four minutes at the
beginning of the second half. Miami took

advantage by extending a 32-26 halftime

edge to a 38-26 bulge. Carolyn Miller
ended the Lady Panther drought with a
layup with 16:10 remaining in the game.

Pitt erased the deficit with an 11-0 run
of its own. Two free throws by Jonna
Huemrich put the Lady Panthers up 41-
40 with 9:08 remaining. Miami could do
no better than to tie the Lady Panthers
the rest of the way.

“We started making a few shots
inside,” Bruce said.  picked up up
on the defensive end of the floor. We
switched up defenses from man-to-man
to zone. They started missing some shots
and we started to rebound. That helped
the comeback because we started getting
some easy possessions.”

The Lady Panthers smothered the
Hurricanes on defense in the second
half, holding Miami to six-of-26 (23 per-
cent) shooting from the floor. While Pitt's
defense was better than usual, the
offense was far below what it has been
this season.

